    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Experimental probability outcome}</m> refers to the result or observation of an event that occurs during an experiment or trial when calculating experimental probability.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Experimental probability}</m> refers to the probability of an event happening based on the results of an actual experiment or trial.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Formula for Experimental Probability:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\textbf{P(E)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of outcomes}}{\textbf{Total number of trials}}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Where;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                P(E) = Experimental probability of event
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Number of outcomes = How many times the event you are interested in occurs
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Total number of trials = The number of times the experiment is repeated
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul> 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                In a bag of marbles, there are red, blue, and green marbles. You pick a marble, note its color, and put it back. You do this <m>30</m> times. You pick a red marble <m>12</m> times. What is the experimental probability of picking a red marble?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Total Number of times a red marble was picked = 12
            </p>
            <p>
                Total number of picks = <m>30</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                To calculate the experimental probability of picking a red marble, we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{P(Red)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of times a red marble was picked}}{\textbf{Total number of picks}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{12}{30}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{2}{5}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp 0.4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the experimental probability of picking a red marble is <m>0.4</m> or <m>40</m>%.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Nanjala rolled a number cube <m>25</m> times and got an even number <m>11</m> times. Predict how many times she might get an even number if she rolls the cube <m>100</m> times.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                From the experiment:
            </p>
            <p>
                Nanjala rolled the number cube <m>25</m> times.
            </p>
            <p>
                She got an even number <m>11</m> times.
            </p>
            <p>
                So, the experimental probability of getting an even number is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{P(Even)} = \amp \frac{\textbf{Number of even outcomes}}{\textbf{Total number of rolls}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{11}{25}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                To predict how many times Nanjala might get an even number in <m>100</m> rolls, we multiply the experimental probability by <m>100</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\textbf{Predicted number of even outcomes} =  \amp \textbf{P(Even)} \times 100</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp \frac{11}{25} \times 100</mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp 44</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, Nanjala might get an even number <m>44</m> times if she rolls the number cube <m>100</m> times.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
